The final release will only be made available to those who have collected each iteration (using an allowlist), and will be released for free.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.

metadata.name: Triangles #42
metadata.description:
Slowly-forming triangles change over time.

Features:

- Palettes are chosen from a curated range. The most common size has six colours, but there is a chance of three, seven or eight.

- Triangle orientation takes two forms. These are subtly blended over time.

- Spacing and grid size are chosen from weighted values.

This piece is designed for display and changes slowly over time. Resizing the window will produce the same pattern, but progress so far will be cleared and the formation process will start again. This is because the pattern is produced by layering over time.

metadata.name: Gravity's End #6
metadata.description:
Gravity's End depicts fictional worlds being warped, distorted, and in rare cases, shattered, due to extreme gravitational forces.

Gravity's End is written with shaders, so a gpu is recommended. It is very gpu friendly, in that only one frame is rendered.

Rarities

- 21 palettes with 5 rare palettes (4% chance for rare).
- 10% chance of getting a shattered world.

Keys: 

's' saves a png in the exact size of the screen.

metadata.name: Evolution #5
metadata.description:
"Evolution" simulates evolution of life forms.

Depending on the "Speed" parameter, every x frame the next evolutionary stage is computed and only the top n life forms stay alive. Each life form also has a life of its own and after some iteration dies. At every new stage random mutations occur, depending on the "Variation probability" parameter. 

Life forms fit within their peers only if they're similar to at least some of them, this percentage is the "Fit ratio".

Each life form has seven features: three for position and size, three for color in HSL space, and one for tolerance. Tolerance means how much a life form tolerates a life form different from itself. The more a circle is transparent, the more tolerant it is.

metadata.name: Leviathan #33
metadata.description:
Leviathan is a generative collection of large bodies made form particles, materialised from the viewers own subconscious. Atoms form gargantuan objects - subatomic monoliths and microscopic giants. Playing with the sense of scale it draws on the viewerâs subjective way of associating forms, a pattern that becomes a mirror, a skeleton for them to project. 

Part artist, part viewer. Leviathan asks us to question these relationships of creation, ownership and meaning. It is a chemical reaction that the artist starts and you finish. A colossal dream we are all sharing together - a leviathan.


Controls:
s or double tap: Download image
1 : Download 2400 x 4000
2 : Download 3600 x 6000
3 : Download 4800 x 8000
4 : Download 7200 x 12000
